That's not her.
That's not her.

01:57.686 --> 02:00.120
That's not her.
That's not her.

02:00.122 --> 02:02.122
That's not her.

02:02.124 --> 02:04.290
That's not her.
That's not her.

02:04.292 --> 02:06.159
That's not her.
Really?

02:06.161 --> 02:08.360
The old Asian man
is not your Meemaw?

02:10.132 --> 02:12.032
And that's not helpful.

02:13.001 --> 02:14.934
You know, I-I got her
an iPhone for Christmas.

02:14.936 --> 02:16.403
I'll see where she is.

02:16.405 --> 02:17.604
Oh, that's nice.

02:17.606 --> 02:19.606
Most people her age
don't embrace technology.

02:19.608 --> 02:21.341
Oh, no, she doesn't
even know she has it.

02:21.343 --> 02:23.443
No, I had my sister
slip it in her bag

02:23.445 --> 02:27.213
so that I can track her
like a sea turtle.

02:27.215 --> 02:29.649
Same as when we lost you
at the zoo.

02:29.651 --> 02:31.518
Uh, for the hundredth time,

02:31.520 --> 02:33.887
I smelled kettle corn
and couldn't find the cart.

02:35.057 --> 02:36.289
Still doesn't explain

02:36.291 --> 02:39.526
how you ended up
on the freeway divider.

02:39.528 --> 02:41.628
Moon Pie!

02:41.630 --> 02:42.829
Meemaw!

02:42.831 --> 02:44.864
I'm so happy to see you!

02:44.866 --> 02:46.166
I'm happy to
see you, too!

02:46.168 --> 02:47.400
Oh.

02:47.402 --> 02:48.668
You got even smaller.

02:48.670 --> 02:50.203
I love it!

02:50.205 --> 02:52.205
Uh, Meemaw, this is Leonard.

02:52.207 --> 02:53.206
Leonard, this is my Meemaw.

02:53.208 --> 02:54.474
Hi. So nice
to finally meet you.

02:54.476 --> 02:56.042
Let me take this
for you, Meemaw.

02:56.044 --> 02:57.210
Thank you.

02:57.212 --> 02:59.212
No. Oh, no.
Now you call her “Constance.”

02:59.214 --> 03:00.680
I call her “Meemaw.”

03:00.682 --> 03:01.948
You have your own Meemaw.

03:01.950 --> 03:03.917
It's not my fault
she died when you were four.

03:05.020 --> 03:07.987
Is that nice to say
to your friend?

03:07.989 --> 03:09.889
It isn't, Meemaw.

03:09.891 --> 03:12.058
Sorry, Leonard.

03:13.295 --> 03:15.728
Can you please
live with us forever?

03:15.730 --> 03:18.098
Oh. (laughs)

03:19.267 --> 03:20.867
That's ridiculous!
If you had

03:20.869 --> 03:23.336
a superpower,
and spent your whole life

03:23.338 --> 03:25.038
being told to suppress it,

03:25.040 --> 03:27.474
when you finally decide
to embrace that power,

03:27.476 --> 03:29.709
why hide in isolation?!

03:29.711 --> 03:31.144
I'm sorry,

03:31.146 --> 03:34.781
and how much money did
<i>your</i> version of <i> Frozen</i> make?!

03:35.917 --> 03:37.484
I'm just saying,

03:37.486 --> 03:39.152
instead of “Let it Go,”
she should really sing,

03:39.154 --> 03:41.454
“Look At Me Hiding in a Freezer
Like a Dove Bar.”

03:42.390 --> 03:45.024
She built an ice castle,
made a snow monster

03:45.026 --> 03:48.027
and gave herself
a complete makeover in one day.

03:48.029 --> 03:49.729
You know what I saw
<i>you</i> do today?

03:49.731 --> 03:52.198
Eat a block of cream cheese
straight from the foil

03:52.200 --> 03:54.701
and lie about it to your wife!

03:56.404 --> 03:58.138
Sorry for eavesdropping,
but did you know

03:58.140 --> 04:00.773
they actually had
the song “Let It Go” in place

04:00.775 --> 04:02.408
before they finalized the story?

04:02.410 --> 04:04.844
Yeah, that's true. In fact,
they liked the song so much,

04:04.846 --> 04:06.446
they retooled
the whole script around it.

04:06.448 --> 04:08.381
Which is probably
why that movie sucks.

04:08.383 --> 04:10.617
Here we are
talking about <i> Frozen,</i>

04:10.619 --> 04:12.018
and yet, you got burned.

04:12.020 --> 04:14.154
Miss, I'm so sorry.

04:14.156 --> 04:15.622
How can you not like that movie?

04:15.624 --> 04:17.624
I just think it gets more credit
than it deserves.

04:17.625 --> 04:19.125
Oh, that's what I said
an hour ago.

04:19.127 --> 04:22.896
Wow. You've been talking
about <i> Frozen</i> for an hour?

04:23.932 --> 04:27.300
You should've seen us
after <i> The Good Dinosaur.</i>

04:27.302 --> 04:31.137
It was a classic western
set in the post-Jurassic period,

04:31.139 --> 04:33.806
and it changed my life.

04:37.612 --> 04:39.112
Are you comfortable?

04:39.114 --> 04:40.813
Very.

04:40.815 --> 04:41.748
It's nice to rest

04:41.750 --> 04:44.317
after 800 flights of stairs.

04:46.688 --> 04:49.689
You were so cute,
huffin' and puffin'.

04:49.691 --> 04:50.924
(knocking)

04:50.926 --> 04:52.458
(gasps)
There's Amy.

04:52.460 --> 04:54.127
I just know
you're gonna hit it off.

04:54.129 --> 04:56.863
You both have
the same fashion sense.

04:57.832 --> 05:01.534
Hello! Come in,
say hi to my Meemaw.

05:01.536 --> 05:03.002
Hi. Nice to meet you.

05:03.004 --> 05:04.537
Nice to meet you, too.

05:04.539 --> 05:05.538
How was your trip?

05:05.540 --> 05:06.606
Wonderful.

05:06.608 --> 05:08.341
And the pilot did
such a good job,

05:08.343 --> 05:10.043
I gave him a butterscotch.

05:10.045 --> 05:12.011
(laughs)
That's great.

05:12.013 --> 05:14.447
And look at you,
sitting in Sheldon's spot.

05:14.449 --> 05:16.049
You know, I don't
even get to sit there.

05:16.051 --> 05:17.283
Yeah.

05:17.285 --> 05:18.985
And you never will.

05:18.987 --> 05:21.821
Ooh, hey, oh, ask her to do the
tissue thing.

05:21.823 --> 05:22.989
Do it, ask her.

05:24.192 --> 05:25.325
Can I have a tissue?

05:25.327 --> 05:26.726
Of course.

05:26.728 --> 05:29.529
(laughs)

05:29.531 --> 05:30.730
Isn't that the best?!

05:30.732 --> 05:32.899
She's like Grandma Spider-Man.

05:33.902 --> 05:35.602
He's been saying that

05:35.604 --> 05:36.903
since he was little.

05:36.905 --> 05:39.405
I still don't know
what it means.

05:39.407 --> 05:41.608
Oh, well, you two sit down
and get to know each other.

05:41.610 --> 05:42.875
I'll get your room ready.

05:42.877 --> 05:44.344
Oh, now don't you go
looking through

05:44.346 --> 05:46.179
my suitcase for presents.

05:46.181 --> 05:47.647
If I did, would I find any?

05:47.649 --> 05:48.881
Maybe.

05:48.883 --> 05:52.719
But you also might find
my brassieres and bloomers.

05:53.755 --> 05:56.623
That's a risk
I'm willing to take!

05:56.625 --> 05:58.157
Well, this is so nice.

05:58.159 --> 06:00.093
He's so excited
to have you here and...

06:00.095 --> 06:03.096
Okay, now let's you and me
get something straight.

06:03.098 --> 06:06.899
He may think that I came
to bake him cookies,

06:06.901 --> 06:09.769
but the real reason
is to size you up.

06:09.771 --> 06:11.971
S-S...

06:11.973 --> 06:13.773
Si-Size me up?

06:13.775 --> 06:16.476
Sheldon's mother may be
okay with you,

06:16.478 --> 06:18.244
but I'm not so easy.

06:18.246 --> 06:19.979
Well, I-I'm...

06:19.981 --> 06:23.182
I'm sure you'll like me
once you get to know me.

06:23.184 --> 06:25.385
Oh, you better hope so.

06:26.788 --> 06:29.389
A Texas Special cattle
and calf car train set

06:29.391 --> 06:30.957
with authentic horn and bell!

06:30.959 --> 06:32.258
Thank you, Meemaw!

06:32.260 --> 06:33.760
Oh, you're welcome, Moon Pie.

06:33.762 --> 06:35.028
Amy, why don't you

06:35.030 --> 06:36.129
look excited?

06:36.131 --> 06:38.231
Well, you get
to watch me play with this!

06:42.070 --> 06:44.370
Oh, I see you're reading <i> Saga.</i>

06:44.372 --> 06:46.439
Yeah, I hear it's pretty good.

06:46.441 --> 06:49.342
It is, and not a lot of comics
have a woman with wings

06:49.344 --> 06:51.878
breastfeeding a baby
right on the cover.

06:51.880 --> 06:54.347
I'll take your word for it.

06:54.349 --> 06:55.348
You should.

06:55.350 --> 06:57.717
He's really looked.

06:58.687 --> 07:01.187
I'm Raj, by the way.

07:01.189 --> 07:02.789
This is Howard.
Hi.

07:02.791 --> 07:04.223
Claire.

07:04.225 --> 07:06.159
Well, I've seen you here before,
Claire.

07:06.161 --> 07:07.660
It's my first time.

07:07.662 --> 07:10.296
I'm looking for inspiration
for this movie I'm writing.

07:10.298 --> 07:11.564
You're a screenwriter?

07:11.566 --> 07:14.801
Well, screenwriter,
slash bartender,

07:14.803 --> 07:18.504
slash, a month away
from living in my car.

07:18.506 --> 07:21.040
Yeah, I get that.

07:21.042 --> 07:22.475
I'm a scientist,

07:22.477 --> 07:23.876
slash party planner,

07:23.878 --> 07:25.878
slash small-dog enthusiast,

07:25.880 --> 07:27.680
slash...

07:27.682 --> 07:30.850
guy who probably should have
stopped at “scientist.”

07:30.852 --> 07:32.752
You're really a scientist?

07:32.754 --> 07:33.853
Well, astrophysicist.

07:33.855 --> 07:35.221
That's perfect.

07:35.223 --> 07:37.890
Do you think I could pick your
brain for my movie some time?

07:37.892 --> 07:39.659
It's animated sci-fi for kids.

07:39.661 --> 07:41.661
Sure. I love animated movies.
He does,

07:41.663 --> 07:44.464
and he has the <i> Lilo & Stitch</i>
collector plates to prove it.

07:46.267 --> 07:49.135
Excuse me for wanting
a little magic in my life.

07:50.472 --> 07:51.771
Here's my number.

07:51.773 --> 07:53.072
Give me a call,
we'll get together.

07:53.074 --> 07:54.941
Yeah, great.
See ya.

07:54.943 --> 07:56.843
Yeah, bye.

07:56.845 --> 07:58.144
What are you doing?

07:58.146 --> 07:59.479
You have a girlfriend.

07:59.481 --> 08:01.147
So?
So,

08:01.149 --> 08:02.515
how do you think she'd feel

08:02.517 --> 08:05.451
about you helping a beautiful
girl with her screenplay?

08:05.453 --> 08:06.953
I wouldn't say
she's beautiful.

08:06.955 --> 08:09.288
Really? You don't think
she's attractive?

08:09.290 --> 08:12.125
I do. I just wouldn't
tell my girlfriend.

08:14.896 --> 08:17.530
Constance, are you sure
I can't pour you some wine?

08:17.532 --> 08:19.499
Oh, no wine for me.

08:19.501 --> 08:23.169
Sheldon's bringing me
my whiskey.

08:23.171 --> 08:25.371
Here you go, Meemaw.
I made it

08:25.373 --> 08:26.472
just how you like--

08:26.474 --> 08:28.541
a lot in a glass.

08:28.543 --> 08:31.310
Thank you, Moon Pie.

08:31.312 --> 08:32.511
Um, curious.

08:32.514 --> 08:34.881
Why do you call Sheldon
“Moon Pie?”

08:34.883 --> 08:36.982
'Cause he's so nummy-nummy.

08:36.985 --> 08:38.885
BOTH:
She could just eat him up.

08:39.654 --> 08:42.054
And I call her “Meemaw”"

08:42.056 --> 08:44.056
because, well, just,
well, look at her.

08:45.393 --> 08:47.326
It's interesting that

08:47.328 --> 08:50.163
Leonard and Penny know
about his nickname

08:50.165 --> 08:51.397
and you don't.

08:51.399 --> 08:53.599
Oh, well, you know,

08:53.601 --> 08:56.035
now-now that I'm hearing it,
it does sound familiar.

08:56.037 --> 08:57.236
How could it?

08:57.238 --> 08:59.572
I never told you,
and you never bothered to ask.

08:59.574 --> 09:01.607
Well, now I know.
Yeah.

09:03.812 --> 09:06.245
So, Penny, I understand
you have a new job.

09:06.247 --> 09:07.313
Yes.

09:07.315 --> 09:08.581
I'm a pharmaceutical
sales rep.

09:08.583 --> 09:09.916
Oh.

09:09.918 --> 09:13.453
It's so wonderful that
you modern gals can have it all.

09:14.355 --> 09:16.722
A husband
and a full-time career.

09:16.724 --> 09:19.892
I have a relationship
and a full-time career, too.

09:19.894 --> 09:22.595
That doesn't bode well.

09:25.233 --> 09:28.334
Why not? You-you just said
it's okay for her to work.

09:28.336 --> 09:32.138
Well, Leonard doesn't need as
much tending to as Sheldon does.

09:32.140 --> 09:33.239
And as Moon Pie explained,

09:33.241 --> 09:35.842
Leonard's work

09:35.844 --> 09:38.211
is more of a hobby.

09:39.681 --> 09:41.581
That's my best friend.

09:41.583 --> 09:42.815
Yeah.

09:42.817 --> 09:44.217
AMY:
Look,

09:44.219 --> 09:46.152
I-I get that you're protective
of your grandson,

09:46.154 --> 09:48.187
but he's an adult now.

09:48.189 --> 09:51.824
Maybe I understand what he needs
better than you do.

09:51.826 --> 09:54.327
I appreciate your honesty, dear.

09:54.329 --> 09:56.229
Thank you.
And here's

09:56.231 --> 09:57.563
some more honesty:

09:57.565 --> 10:00.299
I don't like you very much.

10:02.036 --> 10:03.636
Well, maybe I don't
like you either.

10:03.638 --> 10:04.904
No, no, no, no, no,

10:04.906 --> 10:07.173
no, no, no. Y-You have
to like each other.

10:07.175 --> 10:10.142
Well, we have a 4:30 reservation
at Applebee's.

10:12.347 --> 10:14.347
I think I should leave.

10:14.349 --> 10:15.815
But why?

10:15.817 --> 10:17.416
Other than
you two fighting,

10:17.418 --> 10:20.086
we're having such a good time.

10:20.088 --> 10:22.822
The minute you left the room,
your precious meemaw

10:22.824 --> 10:24.724
started giving me
a really hard time.

10:24.726 --> 10:26.092
I don't need this.

10:26.094 --> 10:27.093
Let her go.

10:27.095 --> 10:29.028
And under no circumstance

10:29.030 --> 10:31.831
will you give her
that engagement ring.

10:33.001 --> 10:33.966
What ring?

10:33.968 --> 10:36.669
Maybe we should give
them some privacy.

10:36.671 --> 10:37.737
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

10:37.739 --> 10:39.705
You go ahead.
I'll catch up with you.

10:41.943 --> 10:44.143
You have
an engagement ring?

10:44.145 --> 10:46.178
Yes.

10:47.015 --> 10:49.482
Penny, did you know
about this?

10:49.484 --> 10:51.350
All right, let's go.

